\pard\sb280\sa40\cf1\b\fs40 1   THE OPEN ROAD -- and the man in the floor\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\sa220\cf3\i Set leaving Riften. Purpose: the breath, and Esbern's comedy re-entry.\cf2\i0\par

\pard\li360\sa140\cf1\b GM:\cf2\b0  Klimmek's been at the Bee and Barb three days now, telling the room what he saw on the 7,000 Steps (Ch.20-22) -- Bjorn's the one who actually sat with him past the first telling, morning after morning. He's come to see the cart off.\f2\lang1033  [they completely forgot who was there. when esbern spoke ismara made an atmoran ice glaive on her hand and prepared to stab him. he sat up looked around and didnt get to say anything before ismara held the ice blade to his throat. so i went to the indignation of being forgoten he went into the lecture before saying who he was. i irl had to remind them that he existed pulled out chapter 20 of the nararative to prove he was real and existed and orion told him to hide in the cart. he shoves the blade away and lectures them on operatiional security and stuff, insists on knowing whos responsible for checking the cart from now on, they let that be ismaras responsibility he pulls out the map and expalins everything. he over hears the rahgot is gone thing but they didnt volunteer the kohnarik thing at all. saijah clues him in on the dagon cult more and he realizes thats what hes been tracking with the grey twine. they really liked the map. they study that for a while get to talking blah blah blah. then they round the bend towards the kahjit karavan]\f0\lang9\par

\pard\sb80\sa60\cf6\b\fs26 >> READ ALOUD\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\li600\ri400\sa220\cf6\i "Dawn breaks over Riften in grey harbor-light, gulls crying over the water. You cinch your packs, count your coin twice, and load everything into the cart while Bjorn checks the wheel-pins the way he always does -- twice. Mable stamps her feet in the traces, impatient to be moving. Beside her the black mare\f2\lang1033  [balthazzar]\f0\lang9  stands perfectly still, already watching the road ahead.\line\line Klimmek crosses over while you're still finishing up and walks straight to Bjorn. He doesn't have a speech ready, and he doesn't try to fake one. 'Three days I told that room the same thing,' he says, 'and half of them just wanted me to shut up and drink.' He's grinning now. 'And then you go and put together six of the best Skyrim's got, and you just -- go.'\line\line He turns to the rest of you before Bjorn can answer. 'All of you.' His voice catches on it, and he waves the rest off with a short laugh, scrubbing a hand across his face.\line\line Bjorn takes the offered hand in both of his instead of shaking it. He's grinning too. 'You kept an old man sane the last three days, lad.' He pulls Klimmek into one hard, quick embrace, claps him twice on the back, and steps away. 'Go on. Get that ale finished before it goes flat.'\line\line The gates swing open. You go. Looking back once, Klimmek is still standing there, one hand raised.\line\line The road takes you north into hills gone gold with the turn of the season. The light is thin and clean. The wheels find their rhythm, and mile by mile an old feeling settles over all of you: ease. Full packs. Paid coin. Warm bread from Riften's ovens, still soft in the saddlebags. A road that asks only that you follow it.\line\line Mable plods on. The black mare walks beside her, head high, ears forward, reading the hills the whole way.\line\line Then, from under the cart's floorboards -- muffled by canvas and the false bottom -- a dry old voice says, with enormous dignity: '...Are we far enough now? My legs fell asleep a day ago.'"\cf2\i0\par

\pard\li360\sa140\cf1\b GM:\cf2\b0  Nobody consciously thought about Esbern since Riften -- but don't assume the TABLE meant to forget him. He genuinely doesn't know whether he was left below on purpose (good tradecraft, out of Thalmor sightlines) or simply forgotten, and his first line should ask that, not accuse it. Play his tone off the table's actual answer, live.\par

\pard\sa140\b ESBERN\b0  (climbing out slow, blinking at the sky like he'd forgotten it existed): "Above deck." A long breath. "I'd nearly forgotten what that felt like." He looks out at the road, the gold hills. "Riverwood road, this time of year. Good traveling weather. We're finally going for that stone."\par

\pard\fi-280\li500\sa120\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 If they own up to forgetting him:\b0  \f2\lang1033 [didnt even give a chance they immediatly threatened him when he showed up] \f0\lang9 he doesn't laugh. "Two days. Anyone could have been under that floor instead of me. A Thalmor plant. A corpse." He straightens, meets their eyes. "I have survived thirty years by checking. Every door. Every floor. If none of you are checking, I am riding into a dragon war with people who will get me killed." A beat. "So. Who's checking the cart from now on?"\par
\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 If they claim it was intentional cover:\b0  he takes them at their word, and it becomes genuinely funny -- he starts complimenting a plan they didn't actually have, in growing detail, until someone cracks.\par

\pard\sa140\b ESBERN\b0  (if they claim it was deliberate): "The false bottom, the silence, waiting till we were clear of the gates -- very sound tradecraft." Then he keeps going. "The timing, too -- letting the guards lose interest in the cart before you moved, instead of rushing it. Most trained agents don't have that discipline." He's already onto a third point. "And not one of you so much as glanced at the floor the whole ride -- misdirection, in case anyone was reading your faces. Professional work." A fourth: "And no one said my name where anyone could overhear it -- compartmentalization. Most units never manage that." A fifth: "And the pace of it -- slow enough through the gate that no one had reason to look twice, fast enough after that no one could catch up if they changed their mind. I felt every bit of that from the floor. That's controlled." He means every word of it. Then, quieter: "You're good. I picked well." A beat. "Thank Talos for that."\par

\pard\sb100\sa240\cf1\b EXIT ->\cf2\b0  Once the laugh settles, he reaches back into the false bottom and pulls out the board.   \b -> 2  ESBERN'S WEB\b0\par

