\pard\sb280\sa40\cf1\b\fs40 2   ESBERN'S WEB -- the strategic briefing\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\sa220\cf3\i Runs on the moving cart, not a stop. Never a wall of lore -- he shows them the web and they pull answers out of it by touching pins.\cf2\i0\par

\pard\sb80\sa60\cf6\b\fs26 >> READ ALOUD\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\li600\ri400\sa220\cf6\i "Esbern pins the map to the cart's inside wall -- thirty years of work down under the sewers finally sees the light of day."\cf2\i0\par

\pard\sa140\b TWO COLORS OF THREAD, and he is fanatical about never letting them touch.\b0\par

\pard\sb160\sa70\cf5\b\fs26 RED THREAD -- the dragons (a war)\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\sb80\sa60\cf6\b\fs26 >> READ ALOUD\f2\lang1033  [this read aloud is bad, i had to improv so we need to go over it and make it better, this is not a read aloud section, "naming each one like hes counting coins" the fuck is that? thats bullshit. just write out him saying the names you loser. then i expalined why bleakfalls was so important]\cf2\b0\f0\fs24\lang9\par

\pard\li600\ri400\sa220\cf6\i "He taps the first pin, then walks two fingers down the row, naming each one like he's counting coins. 'Five of them. Dragon priests, asleep under five mountains, until they weren't.' He stops on the loose one, hanging off its tomb by a thread. 'This one woke on his own and walked out. You saw the tomb -- empty, no mark on it, like he just stood up and left.' A beat. 'The other four, I don't know yet.' He looks at the blank spaces on the map where their tombs should be. 'That's what the Dragonstone would tell me. Without it, I'm guessing at graves.'"\cf2\i0\par

\pard\fi-280\li500\sa120\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2\b0 Five sleeping priests, each pinned to a tomb: \b NAHKRIIN -- VOKUN -- RAHGOT -- OTAR -- MOROKEI.\b0  Rahgot's pin has been moved OFF its tomb and left dangling (the party's own report from Forelhost: he rose and walked out). Esbern keeps touching it like it's sore.\par
\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2\b0 Something that doesn't sit right, and he can't yet say why: the old texts call Rahgot \b the Angry\b0  and Otar \b the Mad\b0  -- priests of fury, not patience. But since they woke, what little word has reached him -- refugees, rumor, a line here and there -- describes calculation instead. Coordination. Rahgot running three operations at once like a general. Otar building quietly in the Reach instead of raging. "Fury doesn't wait," he says, more than once, like it bothers him. "These two are waiting." (He does NOT have KONAHRIK, and he does NOT have the prophecy -- those come from Ismara later, if a player offers Rahgot's tomb. This is the anomaly her information explains, not a blank it fills; he has no way to have suspected a sixth thing existed, and does not.)\par
\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2\b0 Kynesgrove -- the first grave they watched come alive. Dozens of burial mounds in fading ink. And the HOOK: \b blank spaces\b0  -- mounds he knows exist and cannot place. He hates the blanks more than he hates the Thalmor.\par

\pard\sb160\sa70\cf5\b\fs26 GREY THREAD -- the root-rot (an unmaking)\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\sb80\sa60\cf6\b\fs26 >> READ ALOUD\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\li600\ri400\sa220\cf6\i "His hand moves to the other half of the board, and his voice changes -- rougher, more frustrated. He taps the Eldergleam, the Steps, the Throat, Darkwater Crossing -- four now, each one circled twice in charcoal. 'This isn't the Dragon Cult. I've checked it against every pattern I have for them, and none of it fits.' He stares at the blank space in the middle of the circles, where a name should go. 'I don't know who's doing this. I don't know what they want. I only know it isn't the priests.'"\f2\lang1033  [yeah saijah volunteered her knowledge so esbern put together there are 2 apocalypses, she said it before i got to read this so i modified what was said here]\cf2\i0\f0\lang9\par

\pard\fi-280\li500\sa120\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2\b0 The Eldergleam, corrupted. The 7,000 Steps, bleeding. The Throat of the World, circled twice in charcoal. Darkwater Crossing, consumed -- the same refugees they passed on the road weeks back came from there. NOT ONE thread crosses from grey to red -- and if a player ties them together, Esbern physically stops their hand: "No. Two ends of the world, two different authors. Muddle them and you'll parry the wrong one."\par

\pard\sb160\sa70\cf5\b\fs26 WHAT HE SAYS AT THE PINS (in pieces, reacting to what THEY know)\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\fi-280\li500\sa120\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 On the two apocalypses:\b0  "Alduin. The World-Eater\f2\lang1033 .\f0\lang9  He ends this age. A war \f2\lang1033 for the end of the world but a war that \f0\lang9 has a will behind it -- something you can face, fight, kill if you're strong enough." A beat. "The other thing, I can't call a war. I don't know what it wants. I only know the land stays dead after."\f2\lang1033  [didnt get to say this cause saijah volunteered knowledge]\f0\lang9\par
\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 IF THEY MENTION THE MIDDEN'S CRYSTALLIZED CULTIST:\b0  He goes still. "Mythic Dawn." "Two hundred years old. They tried to tear open Oblivion in Dagon's name." He looks at the four circles on the grey thread. "I thought that order was dead. Daedra-worshippers -- Dagon's, specifically. Convinced the Divines are jailers and he's the one who'd break the cage. They murdered Emperor Uriel Septim and his three sons -- with no heir to light the Dragonfires, the ward died, and Oblivion poured straight through the gap. Took another Emperor, Martin Septim, becoming a god to close it."\f2\lang1033  [they didnt mention this but it was still enough for esbern to put together it was the mythic dawn]\f0\lang9\par
\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 On where they're going:\b0  "The Throat of the World is not just \f2\lang1033 a\f0\lang9  holy mountain. It is a PILLAR -- one of the stones that holds the floor of the world up. If the cult cracks it, time itself runs in the cellar. That's what your archer feels."\f2\lang1033  [saijah remembered she was looking for pillars so this played well]\f0\lang9\par
\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 IF THEY SAY THEY'RE HEADED TO IVARSTEAD / THE GREYBEARDS:\b0  he sits back, surprised, and reframes fast, tapping the grey thread. "The monastery? That's not on either thread. That's the OTHER one. The Wall does mention them, eventually -- the Voice matters when a Dragonborn finally stands up -- but that's a later chapter, not this one. Go. I'll mind the pins." He does not try to redirect them toward Bleak Falls; he stays disciplined about the party's own choices, even though the Dragonstone is still the thing he wants most.\f2\lang1033  [saijah framed exactly why they are going there and so this was unecessary esbern was happy to go along for now cause they indicated theyd go to bleakfalls after]\f0\lang9\par
\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 The thing he actually wants\b0  (taps a blank spot): "Bleak Falls Barrow. There is a stone in it -- the Dragonstone -- a map of every dragon grave in Skyrim. Without it we wait for each dragon to find US. Everything we do until we have that stone is a flinch, not a plan." -> Plant it. Don't resolve it. He will say it again the whole campaign.\par

\pard\sb160\sa70\cf4\b\fs26 IF THEY MENTION RAHGOT'S TOMB -- player-driven, do not fish for it\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\li360\sa140\cf1\b GM:\cf2\b0  Fires ONLY if a player -- almost certainly Davinia's, since Ismara holds the memory -- volunteers what the carving in RAHGOT'S tomb actually showed: five priests, a sixth mask above them called KONAHRIK, and the line "when the five become one, the faithful shall ascend." Do not prompt, hint, or have Esbern ask leading questions toward it; this is entirely the player's to offer or withhold, and it's the player's telling, not yours -- never script Ismara's words. The carving is cryptic on its own -- an old prophecy about a mask, nothing that announces itself as a secret. What breaks it open is that it resolves the anomaly he's already noticed and cannot yet explain (Rahgot and Otar's reputation for fury, set against their patient, coordinated behavior since waking), and he does the interpretive work himself, live: not her handing him a conclusion, him reaching one.\f2\lang1033  [i just let him have overheard this in the cart so he already knew about rahgot to save time]\f0\lang9\par

\pard\sb80\sa60\cf6\b\fs26 >> READ ALOUD\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\li600\ri400\sa220\cf6\i "His hands stop. They've been moving pins and twine the whole ride, and now they just stop.\line\line 'The exact words. As close as you can hold them.'\line\line He picks up Rahgot's pin, turns it over once in his fingers, sets it back down where it was hanging.\line\line 'Rahgot the Angry. Otar the Mad. That's what I was taught, forty years ago, off men who'd actually seen them fight. Fury. Priests who broke doors down because they couldn't stand to wait behind one.' A pause, longer than the last. 'And every report I've had since they woke says the opposite. Rahgot running three fronts like he's planning a siege. Otar building in the Reach instead of burning it. I told myself grief changes a man.' He shakes his head. 'Grief doesn't change a man like that.'\line\line He sets the pin down properly this time, hanging straight.\line\line 'The faithful shall ascend. I read that a hundred times and thought it was a hymn. It's an order.' He's quiet a moment, working through it out loud. 'They're not just waiting for him to come back. They're waiting for him to open something. And when it opens, they mean to go through it too.'"\cf2\i0\par

\pard\li360\sa140\cf1\b GM:\cf2\b0  THE STRATEGIC WEIGHT: everything he's told them about "the dragons are one united war" just got more dangerous, not less -- possibly a coalition that plans to turn on itself, which means stopping Alduin and stopping the priests may not be the same fight, and could even cut against each other before the end. Do not resolve this now; it's a live thread for later.\par

\pard\fi-280\li500\sa120\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 THE FOLLOW-UP\b0  (real beat, player-driven): he asks, quietly, not suspicious, just aware of what he's holding now: "How do you know this." What Davinia's player has her answer -- everything, nothing, a version -- is hers entirely.\par

\pard\li360\sa140\cf1\b GM:\cf2\b0  OPEN THREAD, not resolved here: knowing this makes Esbern a bigger target than he already is. Flag it; don't spend it in this scene.\par
\cf1\b GM:\cf2\b0  Esbern is the lore-dump risk incarnate. NEVER let him monologue -- cut him off with a complication, a question, a beat of Ylva groaning. The clue is in the conversation, never in the dump.\par

\pard\sa100\f1\fs20 [PRODUCTION: SOLVED. The briefing IS a real interactive map -- web/esbern_map.html (the GM's own build: draggable pins, physics twine, note cards, the Konahrik unlock toggle), being integrated into the player app. Run this scene with it on screen; the players pull answers out of it by touching pins, exactly as staged above.]\f0\fs24\par

\pard\sb100\sa240\cf1\b EXIT ->\cf2\b0  Dusk finds lantern light around the road's next bend.   \b -> 3  THE TENT FAIR\b0\par

\pard\sb280\sa40\cf1\b\fs40 3   THE RESPITE -- Ahkari's tent fair\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\sa220\cf3\i A deliberate breath. Warmth, color, the world being alive. NO threat.\cf2\i0\par

\pard\sb80\sa60\cf6\b\fs26 >> READ ALOUD\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\li600\ri400\sa220\cf6\i "The road bends around a stand of gold-leaved aspens and the dusk ahead is full of lantern light. Eight tents stand pitched off the verge in a rough ring, dyed saffron and sea-green, patched so many times the patches have patches. A cookfire burns at the center. Rugs are laid out between the tents with goods on them: stoppered bottles in rows, bundles of dried herbs hanging from the tentpoles, blades with a deep southern curve, forged somewhere the trade roads run warmer.\line\line Pack-frames stand against every tentpole, the shoulder straps worn pale and smooth -- the wear of real weight, carried a long way, on foot.\line\line A Khajiit in a coat of a hundred patches spots your cart and comes across the firelight fast, already talking, already sizing you up. 'Travelers -- and with horses under you, and a cart behind them! Ahkari has been waiting all day for someone worth the good prices. Sit, sit, look, touch, everything here is friendlier than it looks. Tea while you decide? The tea comes free. It is the buying after that Ahkari is good at.'"\cf2\i0\par

\pard\sa140\b Why the tents\b0  (only if asked; she says it lightly, an old wound worn smooth): the cities do not let Khajiit inside the walls. So they build their own little towns outside them, a night at a time -- a traveling fair of everything the walled markets never stock.\par

\pard\sb160\sa70\cf5\b\fs26 TRADE -- the exotic fair (reflavored, but every mechanical item cites the Gear list)\cf2\b0\fs24\par

\pard\fi-280\li500\sa120\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 Sun's Dust\b0  -- a dried ash-country fungus, sharp and bitter. A FINISHED consumable, ready to use -- not a raw ingredient (GM: treat as a Cure Poison Potion, per the Gear Doc).\par
\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 Weeper's Tears\b0  -- a marsh venom in a wax-sealed vial, from bogs south of here. A RAW alchemy ingredient (VENITAS[P], GRAVITAS[S] -- Alchemy GM Reference), not finished; feeds Nora/Ismara's bench.\par
\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 Moon Sugar\b0  -- sold openly, a normal caravan good. Raw ingredient (GLACIES[P]/FORTITAS[S]/ANIMA[T] -- Alchemy GM Reference). \b Skooma\b0  -- the refined, finished product, sold quieter, a step removed from the open stall. This caravan is deliberately the easiest place in the campaign to find either. [Skooma's dose/addiction effects are a separate design item, not yet built -- do not adjudicate a first use until that's written.]\par
\cf5\b\bullet\tab\cf2 A handful of Rare Curios\b0  (genuinely Khajiit-caravan stock, priced accordingly -- full stats inline, no lookup needed): \b Alocasia Fruit\b0  (AGILITAS[P], VITALIS[S] -- Shivering Isles fruit, quick and vital), \b Bog Beacon\b0  (ANIMA[P], FORTITAS[S] -- a glowing marsh-growth), \b Comberry\b0  (VENITAS[P], ANIMA[S] -- sharp-flavored, spirit-adjacent), \b Marshmerrow\b0  (VITALIS[P], VENITAS[T] -- restorative, with a faint bite), \b Saltrice\b0  (VITALIS[P], AGILITAS[T] -- Morrowind staple grain, restorative). Ahkari can name where each one is from if asked; she likes explaining her own stock more than most of what she sells.\par
