\pard\li600\ri400\sa220\cf6\i "Ahkari settles onto the crate by the fire, and the caravan children come first -- they always come first -- filling in the ground closest to her knees. She waits until the smallest one is settled. Then she begins, and her voice is not the market voice. It is older and slower, and it carries.\line\line 'In the Rift, south and east of here, there is a wood called Thornheart, and its heart is alive tonight.\line\line A sickness came into that wood once. It went down into the roots and climbed up into the heart-tree, and it made itself a body from what it stole -- bark for its skin, old bone through it like veins, and two wolves of thorn and shadow that slept beneath its feet. It was patient, and it was hungry. It took three woodcutters. Then it took a priestess of Kynareth who had come to heal the trees, and it held all four of them alive inside its trunk, their faces in the wood, and it fed on them the way the sick thing feeds on the well.\line\line Five heroes went into that wood.\line\line The wood did not want them there. It moved its paths behind their backs. It closed the way out and unmade the way forward, and it let them wander until weaker folk would have lain down in the dark. They did not lie down. They learned the wood's own trick -- that it moved when they moved, that it answered what they did -- and they read it the way hunters read a trail, and it brought them, tired and bleeding, to the heart.\line\line The heart-thing rose up to meet them, and their finest blows meant nothing. Fire broke on its bark like water. Arrows turned on the bone. The battle-mage's lance staggered it one single step -- and the ground opened, and the wolves came up out of the earth, and the fight was everywhere at once.\line\line The orc among them saw what the rest could not spare eyes for -- the faces in the trunk, still living. While his companions held the beast and its wolves, he crossed that battlefield and set his blade to the wood-prison, and he cut the first woodcutter free. Then the second. And when he raised his sword to the third -- the priestess -- she found breath enough to beg him: wait. Careful. With the beast roaring at his back and death one heartbeat behind him, that great orc slowed his hands and cut careful, like a mother untangling a child's hair, until she came loose alive.\line\line The beast knew what it had lost. Their lives had been its strength, and its strength was cut away. So it grew -- it poured all its rage into its own body until it stood twice what it had been, and it brought its whole arm down like a felled tree on the one thing standing between it and the priestess.\line\line He had room to run. He stood. One blow, one sound like an anvil rung once, and he was gone -- and the priestess he had freed lived, because he stood.\line\line And she -- barely able to hold her own body upright -- did not run either. She raised Kynareth's ward over the strangers who had come for her and gave the last light in her hands to healing them. And out of the maze came the fifth hero at last, a wizard the wood had swallowed the whole battle long, who had followed the sound of the fight through the dark, and he broke through the treeline with fire in both hands and struck the beast a blow that set it burning.\line\line Then came the small one.\line\line Kyboah. A Khajiit -- like this one, like you, like your mothers and your fathers. No greatsword. No siege-magic. Two hands, wrapped in a fighter's old leather, and every gift the moons ever braided into our people: the speed, the surety, the fall that always lands. He had fought that whole battle already. He was burned and he was bleeding, and what he had left, he spent all at once. He went up -- over the wolves, over the fire, higher than the beast's crown -- and he came down spinning, frost in one hand and flame in the other, and he cut that monster in half. In half, little ones. Crown to root, one stroke, a thing three times his height. It fell in two pieces and went to black sap and dead wood, and the grove stood quiet, and underneath it all the true heart of Thornheart was still beating. It beats tonight. That is his doing.\line\line And the city of Riften heard what he had done for it. And Riften -- stone walls, shut gates, guards who ask our kind to wait outside in the cold -- opened its gate. He walked through the front of it, in daylight, welcomed, while the whole market watched. A Khajiit, little ones. Through the front gate.\line\line The wood is healing. The priestess keeps a temple in the south and prays for him still, so Ahkari has heard. And somewhere under these same two moons that made him quick, Kyboah is walking tonight -- and the moons that made him made every cub at this fire.\line\line Now. To bed.'"\cf2\i0\par

\pard\li360\sa140\cf1\b GM:\cf2\b0  She has no idea who's sitting across her fire -- and the table knows what she cannot: Kyboah is dead, and will never hear this. Let both of those sit however they land; do not point at either. [Sourced to Ch.1-2 -- the Battle for the Heart-Tree of Thornheart Grove, the party's founding deed: the Heart-Keeper (bark and bone, two thorn-wolves), the shifting maze; Azura the orc freed all three captives (two woodcutters, then Danica -- who begged him to cut careful, and he did) and died shielding her from the grown beast's killing blow; Danica, freshly freed, raised a ward and healed; Alfonso, lost in the maze the whole fight, arrived at the end and turned it with Fireball -- his first appearance in the campaign; Kyboah finished it with the spinning aerial cleave, every enchantment at once, bisecting the beast. The living heart still holds Dagon's corruption back -- that is WHY the rot has spread no further on this side. Kyboah's welcome through Riften's gate is canon. DAVINIA AND SAIJAH WERE BOTH THERE (Ismara holds the memory even if she doesn't feel it the way Davinia would). Orion was not part of this one. It is actually about the Lanterns, which is the point: this is how the wider world currently remembers them.]\f2\lang1033  [the party actually said who they were so ahkari knew it was the lanterns or at least some of them, ismara made little ice shadow puppets behind ahakari as the story went on as a cute moment, ahkari made eye contact when she said it was the lanterns and that they were strong and brave and had the strongest kahjit among them]\f0\lang9\par

